  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Three Poems Sent to Someone on Horseback
  author: Choi Dang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I turn my head to look back at Haeyang Castle.
    Beside the walls, the mountains rise jagged and steep.
    Yet those mountains, grown distant, fade from sight—
    how much more will the faces of those within the city walls?

    The mountains wear a melancholy hue,
    the waters murmur with sorrow's sound.
    What comfort could I offer in this moment?
    What balm could ease this aching heart?

    If parting held the promise of return,
    what hardship would a brief farewell bring?
    But knowing we shall meet no more,
    my heart breaks, breaks again—
    endlessly breaking.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Haeyang Castle (海陽城): likely refers to a location in ancient Korea; the specific castle may refer to present-day Haeyang or a similar historical site'
  - key: ''
    value: The three poems are united by the theme of separation and the speaker's journey on horseback away from someone cherished
